===Etymology 2===
{{ja-kanjitab|yomi=k|くれ}}

Likely from the {{m|ja|連用形|tr=ren'yōkei||continuative or stem form}} of verb {{m|ja|暮れる|tr=kureru||to set (''said of the sun or moon''), to get dark}}, from the way that China lies to the [[west]] of Japan, in the direction of the setting sun.<ref name="KDJ">{{R:Kokugo Dai Jiten}}</ref>  This may be related to the famous letter from {{w|Prince Shōtoku}} to {{w|Emperor Yang of Sui}} sent via the {{w|Japanese missions to Sui China|Japanese mission to Sui China in 607}}, wherein we see the first mention of Japan as the {{m|en|Land of the Rising Sun}}, and a description of China as ''Land of the Setting Sun'':

* {{m|zh||日出處天子致書日沒處天子無恙云云}}
: {{m|zh|[[日]][[出]][[處]]|lit=sun + emerge + place}} here refers to Japan, while {{m|zh|[[日]][[沒]][[處]]|lit=sun + sink + place}} refers to China.

In textual Japanese, the term ''Kure'' originally referred more specifically to the ancient [[w:Wu (state)|State of Wu]] (roughly analogous with the modern [[w:Jiangnan|Jiangnan]] region), and later shifted to refer to China as a whole.<ref name="KDJ">{{R:Kokugo Dai Jiten}}</ref><ref name="DJR">{{R:Daijirin}}</ref>

First cited to the ''{{w|Nihon Shoki}}'' of 720.<ref name="KDJ2">{{R:Nihon Kokugo Daijiten 2}}</ref>

